Comment: This sample seems to have two components- an in situ fauna, and a transported assemblage. The in situ fauna is similar to the 1075 coretop (Gs. ruber- pink and other dissolution susceptible specimen) . The transported assemblage is defined by damaged and eroded O. universa and some dissolution resistant species such as G. crassaformis. Many fragments
Less reworking; benthic forams are also common but planktonics are fewer in number.
Different fauna from the overlyig sample (2h-cc)Also there are some pyritized forams.Also found a bivalve with both shells.
There are only a few foraminifera. The form that I am calling G. crassaformis is provbably inaccurate since it has 4 1/2 chambers and crassaformis is restricted to 4 chambers.
Very nice sample and quite similar assaemblage to coretop of 1075.
Dissolution fauna- only rare G. crassiformis and an occasional pink ruber- fecal express?
occasional pyrite; color has changed- it is not green anymore. Instead it is a dull gray brown.
